1	\chapter{Rigidity over $\bar k$: morphisms $\mathbb P^1_{\bar k} \to A_{\bar k}$ are constant}
2	\label{chap:RigidityKbar}
3	
4	This chapter introduces the project's named declaration for the M2.a sub-step of the genus-$0$ Albanese-witness argument: rigidity of morphisms from $\mathbb P^1_{\bar k}$ to a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $A_{\bar k}$ over the algebraic closure $\bar k$. The classical statement (Mumford, \emph{Abelian Varieties}, Chapter~II~\S4) is
5	
6	\begin{quote}
7	  \emph{Let $A$ be an abelian variety of positive dimension over an algebraically closed field $\bar k$. Then every morphism $f \colon \mathbb P^1_{\bar k} \to A$ is constant.}
8	\end{quote}
9	
10	This is the keystone classical input for the C.2.d sub-step of Jacobian.tex \S C.2: the genus-$0$ universal-property step of $\thm{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}$ that, after base-change to $\bar k$, identifies $C_{\bar k} \cong \mathbb P^1_{\bar k}$ and concludes the universal-pointed-morphism factorisation by ruling out positive-dimensional images of $f \colon \mathbb P^1_{\bar k} \to A_{\bar k}$.
11	
12	The full proof of the keystone is gated on a Mathlib pile (cotangent-triviality of an abelian variety + scheme-level $\mathrm d f = 0 \Rightarrow$ $f$ factors through $\Spec \bar k$ + characteristic-$p$ Frobenius / lifting-to-characteristic-$0$ handling); see \cref{sec:RigidityKbar_shared_pile} for the inventory. The iter-126 scaffolding lands the named declaration with a single \texttt{sorry} body whose residual is exactly the keystone above; the body is closed iter-129+ as the shared pile lands.
13	
14	\section{Statement}
15	
16	\begin{theorem}
17	  \label{thm:rigidity_over_kbar}
18	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.rigidity_over_kbar}
19	  Let $\bar k$ be a field (in the use case, an algebraic closure of a base field $k$; the statement is intrinsic to $\bar k$ and does not require an ambient base $k$). Let $C : \mathrm{Over}\,(\Spec \bar k)$ be a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve over $\bar k$ with $\genus(C) = 0$ (i.e.\ $\dim_{\bar k} H^1(C, \mathcal O_C) = 0$). Let $A : \mathrm{Over}\,(\Spec \bar k)$ be a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme over $\bar k$, with identity element $\eta_A \in A(\bar k)$. Let
20	  \[
21	    f \colon C \longrightarrow A
22	  \]
23	  be a morphism of $\bar k$-schemes over $\Spec \bar k$, and let $p \in C(\bar k)$ be a $\bar k$-rational point such that $f(p) = \eta_A$. Then $f$ equals the constant morphism at $\eta_A$:
24	  \[
25	    f \;=\; \bigl(C \to \Spec \bar k \xrightarrow{\,\eta_A\,} A\bigr).
26	  \]
27	
28	  \emph{Encoding note (iter-126).} The Lean signature uses the abstract characterization $\mathtt{SmoothOfRelativeDimension}\ 1\ C.\mathtt{hom} + \mathtt{IsProper}\ C.\mathtt{hom} + \mathtt{GeometricallyIrreducible}\ C.\mathtt{hom} + \genus(C) = 0$ instead of a literal $\mathbb P^1_{\bar k}$ scheme. The two encodings are equivalent over $\bar k$ once the curve has a $\bar k$-rational point (Brauer--Severi triviality + Riemann--Roch on $C \cong \mathbb P^1_{\bar k}$); the abstract form is used because Mathlib snapshot \texttt{b80f227} does not ship a packaged $\mathtt{ProjectiveSpace}\,n\,S$ as a $\mathtt{Scheme.Over}\,S$, and the C.2.b–C.2.d proof decomposition below works for any smooth proper geometrically integral genus-0 curve over $\bar k$ without explicit $\mathbb P^1$ API.
29	\end{theorem}
30	
31	\begin{remark}
32	  \label{rem:rigidity_over_kbar_dim_dichotomy}
33	  \uses{thm:rigidity_over_kbar}
34	  The conclusion is vacuously true when $A$ is zero-dimensional: in that case $A = \Spec \bar k$ and every morphism $\mathbb P^1_{\bar k} \to A$ factors through $\Spec \bar k$ trivially. The substantive content of the theorem is the positive-dimensional case, which decomposes into the steps of \cref{sec:RigidityKbar_proof_decomposition}.
35	\end{remark}
36	
37	\section{Proof decomposition}
38	\label{sec:RigidityKbar_proof_decomposition}
39	
40	The proof of \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} decomposes as follows. We reuse the sub-step labelling of Jacobian.tex \S C.2 so cross-references between the two chapters remain unambiguous.
41	
42	\begin{itemize}
43	  \item[\textbf{(C.2.b)}] \emph{Reduction to the project's rigidity lemma.} Let $c \colon \mathbb P^1_{\bar k} \to A$ denote the constant morphism at $\eta_A$. The conclusion $f = c$ follows from \cref{thm:GrpObj_eq_of_eqOnOpen} (i.e.\ \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Over.ext\_of\_eqOnOpen}, after the iter-125 refactor) applied to $g_1 := f$, $g_2 := c$, $X := \mathbb P^1_{\bar k}$, $Y := A$, once we produce a non-empty open $U \subseteq \mathbb P^1_{\bar k}$ on which $U.\iota \circ f.\mathrm{left} = U.\iota \circ c.\mathrm{left}$ as scheme morphisms. We will take $U := \mathbb P^1_{\bar k}$. The refactored rigidity lemma's hypotheses are trivially satisfied: $\mathbb P^1_{\bar k}$ is smooth (hence reduced) and geometrically irreducible over $\bar k$, and $A$ is proper (hence separated) over $\bar k$.
44	
45	  \item[\textbf{(C.2.c)}] \emph{Image dimension argument.} The morphism $f$ goes from a proper geometrically integral $\bar k$-scheme of dimension $1$ to a smooth proper $\bar k$-scheme of dimension $g := \dim_{\bar k} A$. The set-theoretic image $f(\mathbb P^1_{\bar k}) \subseteq A$ is an irreducible closed subset of $A$ (continuous image of an irreducible space under a proper map). Dichotomy:
46	  \begin{itemize}
47	    \item If $g = 0$: $A = \Spec \bar k$ and the conclusion is vacuous (\cref{rem:rigidity_over_kbar_dim_dichotomy}).
48	    \item If $g \geq 1$ and the image is a single point: the image must be $\{\eta_A\}$ (the pointed hypothesis $f(p) = \eta_A$ pins it). Then $f$ is constant on underlying topological points, and the conclusion follows by promoting set-level equality to scheme-morphism equality (sub-step C.2.e of Jacobian.tex, applied via \cref{thm:GrpObj_eq_of_eqOnOpen}).
49	    \item If $g \geq 1$ and the image is one-dimensional: the image is an irreducible rational curve in $A$. This case is ruled out by the keystone classical input (C.2.d below).
50	  \end{itemize}
51	
52	  \item[\textbf{(C.2.d)}] \emph{Keystone: proper rational curves on an abelian variety are constant.} The remaining case --- the image of $f$ has dimension exactly $1$ --- is ruled out by Mumford's classical fact stated in the chapter introduction. Two standard proofs are sketched in Jacobian.tex \S C.2.d (the dual-abelian-variety route via $\Pic^0(\mathbb P^1_{\bar k}) = 0$, and the cotangent-bundle route via triviality of $\Omega_{A/\bar k}$). Both routes require Mathlib infrastructure not currently present (see \cref{sec:RigidityKbar_shared_pile}).
53	
54	  \item[\textbf{(C.2.e)}] \emph{Promotion of set-level equality to scheme-morphism equality.} Standard reduced-source / separated-target argument, integrated into the application of \cref{thm:GrpObj_eq_of_eqOnOpen} in C.2.b.
55	\end{itemize}
56	
57	\section{The shared cotangent-vanishing Mathlib pile}
58	\label{sec:RigidityKbar_shared_pile}
59	
60	The C.2.d keystone above (\emph{morphisms from $\mathbb P^1_{\bar k}$ to a positive-dimensional abelian variety over $\bar k$ are constant}) and the genus-$0$ identification alternative of \cref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} (M2.d-alt of STRATEGY.md, which sidesteps Riemann--Roch by running the cotangent-vanishing argument directly) depend on the same Mathlib pile. STRATEGY.md \S M2.d-alt names this the \emph{shared cotangent-vanishing pile}. The pile decomposes into:
61	
62	\begin{itemize}
63	  \item[(i)] \emph{Abelian-variety cotangent triviality.} Mathlib gap (PHANTOM, confirmed iter-124 + iter-125 spot-checks): the lemma $\Omega_{A/k}$ is trivial of rank $\dim A$ for a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $A$ over a field $k$, via the left-invariant-form construction. Likely candidate name: \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.AbelianVariety.cotangent\_trivial} or \texttt{GroupScheme.Omega\_trivial}. Estimated build: 200--400 LOC.
64	
65	  \item[(ii)] \emph{Scheme-level $\mathrm d f = 0$ implies $f$ factors through $\Spec k$.} The companion algebraic fact: if a morphism $f \colon X \to Y$ between smooth proper $k$-schemes has $\mathrm d f \colon f^* \Omega_{Y/k} \to \Omega_{X/k}$ the zero map (e.g.\ because $\Omega_{Y/k}$ is trivial and $H^0(X, \Omega_{X/k}) = 0$), then $f$ factors through the constant morphism. In characteristic $0$ this is the standard differential-vanishing-implies-constancy argument. In characteristic $p > 0$ it requires the Frobenius lifting / iteration discussion below. Estimated build: 200--400 LOC.
66	
67	  \item[(iii)] \emph{Characteristic-$p$ handling.} Three options on the table:
68	  \begin{itemize}
69	    \item \emph{Frobenius iteration.} Replace $f$ with $f \circ F^n$ for the $n$-th iterate of Frobenius and arrange so the iterated map has zero differential; descent of the conclusion to the original $f$ uses smoothness of $A$.
70	    \item \emph{Mumford's argument} (\emph{Abelian Varieties}, Chapter~II~\S4): exploits the fact that abelian varieties contain no rational curves in characteristic $p$.
71	    \item \emph{Lifting to characteristic $0$.} Lift $A$ to characteristic $0$ via Witt vectors, run the differential argument over the lifted base, then descend.
72	  \end{itemize}
73	  Estimated build for whichever option is chosen: 200--400 LOC. The iter-126 mathlib-analogist consult is scoped to choose between these options based on current Mathlib coverage of Frobenius / Witt-vector / lifting infrastructure.
74	
75	  \item[(iv)] \emph{Serre duality on a smooth proper curve.} Used by the M2.d-alt genus-$0$ identification alternative, not by C.2.d itself. Mathlib gap: PHANTOM (verified absent iter-124). Estimated build: 200--400 LOC.
76	\end{itemize}
77	
78	Total pile cost: 800--1500 LOC (this is the multi-iter shared build whose iter-range is the dominant cost driver of M2 closure per STRATEGY.md \S Sequencing). The iter-126 mathlib-analogist scoping consult informs the iter-129+ build directives.
79	
80	\section{Use in the project}
81	
82	The named declaration $\thm{thm:rigidity_over_kbar}$ is consumed by:
83	
84	\begin{itemize}
85	  \item \textbf{M2.b genus-0 witness (iter-127 scaffold, then later body).} The \texttt{isAlbaneseFor} field of \texttt{JacobianWitness C} for a genus-$0$ curve $C$ over $k$ branches on whether $C(k) \neq \emptyset$. When $C(k) \neq \emptyset$, \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} is invoked (after base-changing $f$ to $\bar k$ and applying the Galois-descent-of-morphism-equality step of \cref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} sub-step C.2.f to descend back to $k$; this Galois-descent step is one of the Mathlib gaps catalogued in \cref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} \S C.2.g and may be avoided altogether under the strategic alternative "direct over-k rigidity" discussed in STRATEGY.md); when $C(k) = \emptyset$, the field is vacuously true (no marked points exist).
86	  \item \textbf{No other in-tree consumer.} The declaration is project-internal; it is not consumed by any \texttt{Cohomology/*.lean}, \texttt{Genus.lean}, \texttt{AbelJacobi.lean}, or \texttt{Differentials.lean} declaration.
87	\end{itemize}
88	
89	\section{Mathlib status}
90	
91	The named declaration is project-internal scaffolding for iter-126. The shared cotangent-vanishing pile (\cref{sec:RigidityKbar_shared_pile}) is upstream Mathlib gap-fill work that the project will execute in-tree over iter-129+ per the iter-126 user hint endorsing the long-LOC Mathlib gap-fill path. Each of the pile's four pieces (i)--(iv) is a meaningful Mathlib contribution candidate; the project will land them as in-tree material first, with upstream PRs as follow-on work after they are stable.
